      Notional nickel
   =20
 =20

If you want to make=C2=A0batteries or cars, you might need nickel. If you b=
uy some nickel from a nickel merchant, and she delivers it to you, and you =
open the box, and the box is full of rocks painted to look like nickel, you=
 will be disappointed. You will not be able to make a battery or a car with=
 a box of rocks.
If you are in the business of building batteries or cars, you might want to=
 hedge your exposure to global nickel prices by trading nickel futures on a=
n exchange like the London Metal Exchange. Or if you are a hedge fund or ba=
nk with a view on commodity prices, you might want to trade nickel=C2=A0fut=
ures to express that view. These futures do not, in the first instance, inv=
olve any nickel. If you buy nickel futures, it is purely a financial trade:=
 If the price of nickel goes up between now and when the futures expire, yo=
u get paid money; if it goes down, you pay money. You buy the nickel for th=
e batteries or cars through normal industrial channels =E2=80=94=C2=A0your =
nickel merchant=C2=A0delivers nickel in the types and quantities you need=
=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0and the point of the futures=C2=A0is just to have a fi=
nancial hedge to your cost of buying actual nickel.
But for the futures to work they need to have some connection to actual nic=
kel, which means that the futures are=C2=A0deliverable:=C2=A0If you own nic=
kel futures that are about to expire, instead of cashing them out you can i=
nstead pay the money and take delivery of the nickel. A staple of trading-f=
loor comedy is the story=C2=A0that some junior trader forgot to cash out he=
r open futures position and so one morning five trucks full of nickel showe=
d up outside the office, but in fact it would be exceedingly impractical to=
 never know whether or where you might=C2=A0have to deliver cargos of nicke=
l, so the LME has a more efficient system. The system is that there are cer=
tain warehouses affiliated with the LME that store a certain amount of nick=
el on behalf of nickel futures traders, and =E2=80=9Cdelivery=E2=80=9D of n=
ickel when a contract expires consists of changing the ownership of some of=
 the nickel in one of the warehouses.
  [1]
=C2=A0If I own nickel in an LME warehouse and sell a futures contract, and =
you buy the contract, and you let it expire and take delivery of the nickel=
, what you actually get is a little notation =E2=80=94=C2=A0called a =E2=80=
=9Cwarrant=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0saying that now you own the nickel in th=
e warehouse.
If one night a supervillain snuck into all the LME warehouses and stole all=
 the nickel, and replaced it with rocks, and hypnotized all the guards into=
 thinking it was still there, and hacked into the security cameras to make =
them show that the nickel was still there, it is tempting to think that the=
 futures market could continue=C2=A0indefinitely in blissful ignorance.=C2=
=A0It is primarily a financial market, not an industrial one; if you get a =
warrant on LME warehouse nickel you are probably=C2=A0not going to go to th=
e warehouse immediately to take possession of your nickel and turn it into =
cars or batteries. Like  Yap money stones, the warehouse nickel is still us=
eful for financial trading even if it is=C2=A0not actually there, or=C2=A0n=
ot actually nickel.
But to make the financial contracts work, there has to be some connection b=
etween the warehouse nickel and regular=C2=A0nickel. It has to be=C2=A0poss=
ible=C2=A0to take warehouse nickel out of the warehouses to transform into =
cars or batteries, or to put nickel into the warehouses if you don=E2=80=99=
t need it for industrial uses. There is a thin connection between the abstr=
act financial nickel in the warehouses and the industrial nickel in the rea=
l world, but there is a connection.=C2=A0Nickel=C2=A0and people=C2=A0do hav=
e to go in and out of the warehouses. And if you go into a warehouse to tak=
e out some nickel and find out that it=E2=80=99s rocks, that=E2=80=99s =E2=
=80=A6=C2=A0bad? Kind of bad? Not=C2=A0that=C2=A0bad? Funny? Philosophicall=
y illuminating?
Bloomberg=E2=80=99s   Jack Farchy, Archie Hunter and Mark Burton report:

JPMorgan Chase & Co. owned the London Metal Exchange nickel contracts that =
turned out to be backed by bags of stones rather than metal, according to p=
eople familiar with the matter.
The LME last week announced it had canceled nine nickel contracts =E2=80=94=
 worth about $1.3 million =E2=80=94 after discovering =E2=80=9Cirregulariti=
es=E2=80=9D at a certain warehouse, which Bloomberg has reported was owned =
by Access World. The news has been met with shock in the metals world, beca=
use LME contracts are generally viewed as beyond question.
JPMorgan was the owner of the nine invalidated contracts, according to peop=
le familiar with the matter. The bank registered the bags of material as be=
ing deliverable against LME contracts in early 2022, said the people, who a=
sked not to be identified discussing private information.
There=E2=80=99s no suggestion that JPMorgan did anything wrong. The materia=
l was already inside Access World=E2=80=99s Rotterdam warehouse when the ba=
nk bought it several years ago, according to one of the people.

It=E2=80=99s so good. JPMorgan, which does not make batteries or cars, boug=
ht bags of abstract nickel years ago. It took delivery of that nickel, not =
in the sense that a truck full of nickel showed up on Park Avenue but in th=
e sense that an entry was made, on the ledger of the warehouse, saying that=
 the bags of nickel in Row X, Shelf Y now belonged to JPMorgan.
JPMorgan then used that nickel for its intended purposes for years. Those p=
urposes were to=C2=A0write financial contracts referencing that nickel. The=
 nickel worked perfectly well for those purposes =E2=80=94=C2=A0JPMorgan=E2=
=80=99s derivative contracts traded and paid off normally =E2=80=94=C2=A0fo=
r years, even though the nickel was not in fact nickel, just bags of rocks.
And then one day a warehouse worker, like, stubbed his toe against JPMorgan=
=E2=80=99s nickel and was like =E2=80=9Chmm that=E2=80=99s not the sound ni=
ckel makes when you kick it=E2=80=9D and opened the bags and found rocks.
  [2]
=C2=A0And then the LME dutifully reported that some nickel was not nickel, =
and JPMorgan=E2=80=99s nickel warrants were transformed into rocks warrants=
.
  [3]
=C2=A0But it=E2=80=99s all just a random accident? The purpose of JPMorgan=
=E2=80=99s nickel was not to be turned into batteries or cars, but to sit i=
n a warehouse. It was doing a great job of that, until someone noticed!

