An uncontrolled bank failure is very bad for everyone. Banks are not genera=
lly constructed=C2=A0in such a way that they could withstand all their mone=
y fleeing at once: If there is a run and all the depositors take their mone=
y out at once, the bank will be forced to sell everything hastily and will =
probably end up without enough money to pay back the depositors, leaving ot=
her creditors and shareholders with nothing. At a big international bank=C2=
=A0that is active in the capital markets, this problem is probably worse:=
=C2=A0Derivatives counterparties and overnight lenders will flee, traders w=
ill bet against the bank=E2=80=99s positions, markets will be stressed and =
the bank will probably=C2=A0collapse rapidly and in a way that leaves too l=
ittle value for everyone.
If you are a national bank regulator and one of your biggest banks seems to=
 be teetering on the edge of an uncontrolled failure, here are some things =
that are generally true:
=09You know that an uncontrolled failure would be bad for that bank, for it=
s shareholders and creditors and depositors and other stakeholders.=09You k=
now that they know it.=09You know that an uncontrolled failure would be bad=
 for the rest of your banking system, and your economy, and the world=E2=80=
=99s banking system.=09You are not inclined to run a risk of that happening=
 at, you know, a 30% or 40% probability. =E2=80=9CEhh let=E2=80=99s see wha=
t happens, maybe it won=E2=80=99t fail, maybe everything will be fine=E2=80=
=9D: not usually the position of the national bank regulator.=09You will wa=
nt to arrange some sort of rescue, preferably one where the struggling bank=
 is acquired by a bigger and more solid bank, not-preferably-but-inevitably=
 one where the national regulator and central bank provide some guarantees =
to the acquirer to further reassure the market.=09You know that the bigger =
and more solid bank can=E2=80=99t really say no to doing the rescue: It=C2=
=A0also=C2=A0knows that an uncontrolled failure of the struggling bank woul=
d be very bad for the rest of the banking system, and for itself, and that =
you can make things particularly bad for it if it says no.=09You pretty muc=
h have to do any rescue between the close of US markets on Friday and the o=
pening in Asia on Monday: Doing it during market hours is too chaotic, and =
doing it overnight on a weekday doesn=E2=80=99t give you enough time.=09Bet=
ween the time that you start getting nervous and the time that you actually=
 do the rescue, you have to put a brave face on things. =E2=80=9CStruggling=
 Bank is doing just great, its capital and liquidity are strong, it has acc=
ess to very large but not at all panicky central bank liquidity facilities,=
 what are you even talking about, why would anyone worry,=E2=80=9D you say =
at the press conference on Wednesday, and then you go back to your office t=
o continue arranging a rescue for the weekend.

This is all a pretty standard playbook for, you know, once-a-decade-or-two =
banking crises, but it is not really=C2=A0written down=C2=A0anywhere, excep=
t eventually in the memoirs of central bankers and regulators.=C2=A0Mostly =
for good reasons, there will not be a law saying, like, =E2=80=9Cif the nat=
ional bank regulator is worried about a 20% probability of an uncontrolled =
bank failure, she can pick a different bank and force it to buy the struggl=
ing bank over a weekend, and name her own price.=E2=80=9D It=E2=80=99s just=
, if you are the regulator, you kind of know you can do that, and you know =
that you should, and you know that the relevant bankers also know it.
And so if you meet with the chief executive officer of the struggling bank =
on Thursday and say =E2=80=9Chey your biggest rival is gonna buy you this w=
eekend at a 90% discount to your closing stock price tomorrow,=E2=80=9D and=
 he says =E2=80=9Cwhat, no, what gives you the right to do that,=E2=80=9D y=
ou can just sort of stare at him for a minute and he=E2=80=99ll say =E2=80=
=9Coh right=E2=80=9D and agree to the deal.=C2=A0
He is a banker and his counterpart is a banker and you are a bank regulator=
 and you all know the unwritten rules, but not everyone does. The strugglin=
g bank=E2=80=99s=C2=A0shareholders, for instance, might get angry about bei=
ng forced to sell their shares at a 90% discount. =E2=80=9CThis is illegal,=
 we have rights,=E2=80=9D they might say. And your response might reasonabl=
y be =E2=80=9Cwell, no, if we hadn=E2=80=99t done this deal over the weeken=
d, the bank would have gone into uncontrolled failure, which would have had=
 many very bad consequences, the least consequential of which is that your =
shares would be worth zero, so be happy you got something.=E2=80=9D
But=C2=A0their response might reasonably be: =E2=80=9CWhat? Prove it. I don=
=E2=80=99t know that the bank would have gone to zero over the weekend, and=
 in fact on Wednesday you were saying that its capital position was great a=
nd there was nothing to worry about. Now you are telling me it=E2=80=99s a =
zero, but I don=E2=80=99t believe you.=E2=80=9D
And for various reasons, it will be=C2=A0hard=C2=A0for you to prove that th=
e bank was going to zero. For one thing, you did=C2=A0keep saying everythin=
g was fine. And there is a general fog of war and   quantum uncertainty of =
bank assets. And it is hard to prove the counterfactual: The stuff you did =
to stabilize the system over the weekend might have made the struggling ban=
k solvent. Also, though, you might be wrong? Like, if you thought there was=
 a 30% chance of an uncontrolled failure, you probably took decisive steps =
to end it over the weekend, which means there was a 70% chance you were wro=
ng. Not a risk you wanted to take, as a bank regulator, but maybe one the s=
hareholders would have been willing to take.
Or politicians might say =E2=80=9Cwhat gave you the right to do this bank m=
erger=C2=A0over the weekend, put thousands of bankers out of work,=C2=A0and=
 promise tons of taxpayer money to backstop the combined bank?=E2=80=9D And=
 you will mutter a legal answer =E2=80=94=C2=A0you do=C2=A0have=C2=A0lawyer=
s, and they can make creative use of the written rules in an emergency =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0but the real deep intuitive answer is that bank rescues follow =
an unwritten and ad hoc playbook=C2=A0and you did what you thought you had =
to. But nobody wants to hear that answer and you will save it for your memo=
ir.
