 will provide these deposits directly to customers whose accounts are assoc=
iated with the digital-asset banking businesses. =E2=80=A6
Today's transaction included the purchase of about $38.4 billion of Signatu=
re Bridge Bank, N.A.'s assets, including loans of $12.9 billion purchased a=
t a discount of $2.7 billion. Approximately $60 billion in loans will remai=
n in the receivership for later disposition by the FDIC. =E2=80=A6
The FDIC estimates the cost of the failure of Signature Bank to its Deposit=
 Insurance Fund to be approximately $2.5 billion.

Flagstar bought the assets it wanted and left the ones it didn=E2=80=99t; i=
t also assumed the=C2=A0deposits=C2=A0it wanted (everything but crypto) and=
 left the rest. Less than a month ago,  US banking regulators issued a =E2=
=80=9Cjoint statement on liquidity risks resulting from crypto-asset market=
 vulnerabilities,=E2=80=9D warning banks that if they took crypto deposits =
they would be more vulnerable to a bank run. Then there was a series of ban=
k runs and a global banking crisis. Who would want those crypto deposits no=
w?
Meanwhile there  seems to be no buyer for all of Silicon Valley Bank, but t=
here is   this amazing story:

The former owner of=C2=A0Silicon Valley Bank, seized earlier this month by =
regulators, asked a judge to force federal regulators to return as much as =
$2 billion the company says it needs to reorganize in bankruptcy.
SVB Financial Group=C2=A0was cut off from the money after the bank was take=
n over by regulators, who control the bank=E2=80=99s deposits, but not asse=
ts owned by SVB. The parent company has as much as $2 billion in several ac=
counts, including three at its former bank, which was renamed=C2=A0Bridge B=
ank=C2=A0after it was taken over. Regulators at the=C2=A0Federal Deposit In=
surance Corporation=C2=A0have refused to give SVB access to the accounts, a=
ccording to court papers filed Sunday.
The dispute threatens to disrupt SVB=E2=80=99s attempt to repay more than $=
3 billion the company owes bondholders. SVB filed for bankruptcy last week =
in order to reorganize its non-bank assets and repay creditors.=C2=A0

The FDIC has taken over Silicon Valley Bank and is trying to sell it off, b=
ut it seems like it may not succeed in selling the bank for more than it ow=
es depositors, meaning that the FDIC =E2=80=94=C2=A0which has promised to p=
ay all SVB depositors, including uninsured ones =E2=80=94=C2=A0might lose m=
oney on the deal.
Meanwhile the holding company=E2=80=99s bondholders, who are in some rough =
hypothetical sense junior to the depositors, seem to be poised to get much =
of their money back, because the holding company had assets other than the =
bank. One of those assets was $2 billion in cash. But that cash was held at=
 SVB, and the FDIC, as a rather understandable matter of rough justice, isn=
=E2=80=99t giving it back.
And here is  a proposal from Jeffrey Gordon for =E2=80=9Cstorage=E2=80=9D b=
ank accounts at Silicon Valley Bank, in which holders would own stock in th=
e bank and forfeit that stock if they redeemed their deposits early. Make t=
he depositors owners of the bank and maybe they won=E2=80=99t run on it.

