<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you want to make=C2=A0batteries or cars, yo=
u might need nickel. If you buy some nickel from a nickel merchant, and she=
 delivers it to you, and you open the box, and the box is full of rocks pai=
nted to look like nickel, you will be disappointed. You will not be able to=
 make a battery or a car with a box of rocks.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you are in the business of building batteri=
es or cars, you might want to hedge your exposure to global nickel prices b=
y trading nickel futures on an exchange like the London Metal Exchange. Or =
if you are a hedge fund or bank with a view on commodity prices, you might =
want to trade nickel=C2=A0futures to express that view. These futures do no=
t, in the first instance, involve any nickel. If you buy nickel futures, it=
 is purely a financial trade: If the price of nickel goes up between now an=
d when the futures expire, you get paid money; if it goes down, you pay mon=
ey. You buy the nickel for the batteries or cars through normal industrial =
channels =E2=80=94=C2=A0your nickel merchant=C2=A0delivers nickel in the ty=
pes and quantities you need=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0and the point of the future=
s=C2=A0is just to have a financial hedge to your cost of buying actual nick=
el.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But for the futures to work they need to have =
some connection to actual nickel, which means that the futures are=C2=A0<em=
>deliverable:=C2=A0</em>If you own nickel futures that are about to expire,=
 instead of cashing them out you can instead pay the money and take deliver=
y of the nickel. A staple of trading-floor comedy is the story=C2=A0that so=
me junior trader forgot to cash out her open futures position and so one mo=
rning five trucks full of nickel showed up outside the office, but in fact =
it would be exceedingly impractical to never know whether or where you migh=
t=C2=A0have to deliver cargos of nickel, so the LME has a more efficient sy=
stem. The system is that there are certain warehouses affiliated with the L=
ME that store a certain amount of nickel on behalf of nickel futures trader=
s, and =E2=80=9Cdelivery=E2=80=9D of nickel when a contract expires consist=
s of changing the ownership of some of the nickel in one of the warehouses.=
<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; t=
ext-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-co=
lor: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: trans=
parent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0If I own nickel in an LME warehouse and sell a futures contract, =
and you buy the contract, and you let it expire and take delivery of the ni=
ckel, what you actually get is a little notation =E2=80=94=C2=A0called a =
=E2=80=9Cwarrant=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0saying that now you own the nickel=
 in the warehouse.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If one night a supervillain snuck into all the=
 LME warehouses and stole all the nickel, and replaced it with rocks, and h=
ypnotized all the guards into thinking it was still there, and hacked into =
the security cameras to make them show that the nickel was still there, it =
is tempting to think that the futures market could continue=C2=A0indefinite=
ly in blissful ignorance.=C2=A0It is primarily a financial market, not an i=
ndustrial one; if you get a warrant on LME warehouse nickel you are <em>pro=
bably=C2=A0</em>not going to go to the warehouse immediately to take posses=
sion of your nickel and turn it into cars or batteries. Like <a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30911506.258434/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cu=
ZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvMzA4MGQzNjgtZDVhYS00MTI1LWEyMTAtNzE0ZTM3MDg3MDE3/607f07=
ceef4b8524a319a23cB588f9f59" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope"=
 target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Yap money stones</a>, the warehouse n=
ickel is still useful for financial trading even if it is=C2=A0<em>not actu=
ally there</em>, or=C2=A0<em>not actually nickel</em>.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But to make the financial contracts work, ther=
e has to be <em>some</em> connection between the warehouse nickel and regul=
ar=C2=A0nickel. It has to be=C2=A0<em>possible=C2=A0</em>to take warehouse =
nickel out of the warehouses to transform into cars or batteries, or to put=
 nickel into the warehouses if you don=E2=80=99t need it for industrial use=
s. There is a thin connection between the abstract financial nickel in the =
warehouses and the industrial nickel in the real world, but there is a conn=
ection.=C2=A0Nickel=C2=A0and people=C2=A0do have to go in and out of the wa=
rehouses. And if you go into a warehouse to take out some nickel and find o=
ut that it=E2=80=99s rocks, that=E2=80=99s =E2=80=A6=C2=A0bad? Kind of bad?=
 Not=C2=A0<em>that=C2=A0</em>bad? Funny? Philosophically illuminating?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bloomberg=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.ma=
il.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30911506.258434/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJn=
LmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMjAvanBtb3JnYW4tb3duZWQtdGhlLWxtZS1uaWN=
rZWwtdGhhdC13YXMtYWN0dWFsbHktYmFncy1vZi1zdG9uZXM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDMyMTIzX01PTk=
VZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09M=
jMwMzIxJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2c0e0036" =
itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"c=
olor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; =
border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color:=
 #ccc;">  Jack Farchy, Archie Hunter and Mark Burton report</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">JPMorgan Chase &amp; Co. owned the London Meta=
l Exchange nickel contracts that turned out to be backed by bags of stones =
rather than metal, according to people familiar with the matter.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The LME last week announced it had canceled ni=
ne nickel contracts =E2=80=94 worth about $1.3 million =E2=80=94 after disc=
overing =E2=80=9Cirregularities=E2=80=9D at a certain warehouse, which Bloo=
mberg has reported was owned by Access World. The news has been met with sh=
ock in the metals world, because LME contracts are generally viewed as beyo=
nd question.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">JPMorgan was the owner of the nine invalidated=
 contracts, according to people familiar with the matter. The bank register=
ed the bags of material as being deliverable against LME contracts in early=
 2022, said the people, who asked not to be identified discussing private i=
nformation.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There=E2=80=99s no suggestion that JPMorgan di=
d anything wrong. The material was already inside Access World=E2=80=99s Ro=
tterdam warehouse when the bank bought it several years ago, according to o=
ne of the people.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It=E2=80=99s so good. JPMorgan, which does not=
 make batteries or cars, bought bags of abstract nickel years ago. It took =
delivery of that nickel, not in the sense that a truck full of nickel showe=
d up on Park Avenue but in the sense that an entry was made, on the ledger =
of the warehouse, saying that the bags of nickel in Row X, Shelf Y now belo=
nged to JPMorgan.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">JPMorgan then used that nickel for its intende=
d purposes for <em>years</em>. Those purposes were to=C2=A0<em>write financ=
ial contracts referencing that nickel</em>. The nickel worked perfectly wel=
l for those purposes =E2=80=94=C2=A0JPMorgan=E2=80=99s derivative contracts=
 traded and paid off normally =E2=80=94=C2=A0for years, even though the nic=
kel was not in fact nickel, just bags of rocks.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then one day a warehouse worker, like, stu=
bbed his toe against JPMorgan=E2=80=99s nickel and was like =E2=80=9Chmm th=
at=E2=80=99s not the sound nickel makes when you kick it=E2=80=9D and opene=
d the bags and found rocks.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !importa=
nt; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0And then the LME dutifully reported that some nickel was not nick=
el, and JPMorgan=E2=80=99s nickel warrants were transformed into rocks warr=
ants.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #0000=
00; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bott=
om-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: =
transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0But it=E2=80=99s all just a random accident? The purpose of JPMor=
gan=E2=80=99s nickel was not to be turned into batteries or cars, but to si=
t in a warehouse. It was doing a great job of that, until someone noticed!<=
/p>
