<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Rule of law</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">An uncontrolled bank failure is very bad for e=
veryone. Banks are <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click=
/30911506.258434/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLz=
IwMjMtMDMtMTcvYmlnLWJhbmtzLXRydXN0LWZpcnN0LXJlcHVibGljLXdpdGgtdGhlaXItbW9uZ=
Xk_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDMyMTIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNl=
PW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwMzIxJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07=
ceef4b8524a319a23cB7fea1656" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope"=
 target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: solid; background-color: #ccc;">not generally constructed</a>=C2=A0in =
such a way that they could withstand all their money fleeing at once: If th=
ere is a run and all the depositors take their money out at once, the bank =
will be forced to sell everything hastily and will probably end up without =
enough money to pay back the depositors, leaving other creditors and shareh=
olders with nothing. At a big international bank=C2=A0that is active in the=
 capital markets, this problem is probably worse:<em>=C2=A0</em>Derivatives=
 counterparties and overnight lenders will flee, traders will bet against t=
he bank=E2=80=99s positions, markets will be stressed and the bank will pro=
bably=C2=A0collapse rapidly and in a way that leaves too little value for e=
veryone.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you are a national bank regulator and one o=
f your biggest banks seems to be teetering on the edge of an uncontrolled f=
ailure, here are some things that are generally true:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You know that an uncontrolled failure=
 would be bad for that bank, for its shareholders and creditors and deposit=
ors and other stakeholders.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You kn=
ow that they know it.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You know tha=
t an uncontrolled failure would be bad for the rest of your banking system,=
 and your economy, and the world=E2=80=99s banking system.</li>=09<li style=
=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You are not inclined to run a risk of that happeni=
ng at, you know, a 30% or 40% probability. =E2=80=9CEhh let=E2=80=99s see w=
hat happens, maybe it won=E2=80=99t fail, maybe everything will be fine=E2=
=80=9D: not usually the position of the national bank regulator.</li>=09<li=
 style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You will want to arrange some sort of rescue=
, preferably one where the struggling bank is acquired by a bigger and more=
 solid bank, not-preferably-but-inevitably one where the national regulator=
 and central bank provide some guarantees to the acquirer to further reassu=
re the market.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You know that the b=
igger and more solid bank can=E2=80=99t really say no to doing the rescue: =
It=C2=A0<em>also=C2=A0</em>knows that an uncontrolled failure of the strugg=
ling bank would be very bad for the rest of the banking system, and for its=
elf, and that you can make things particularly bad for it if it says no.</l=
i>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You pretty much have to do any rescu=
e between the close of US markets on Friday and the opening in Asia on Mond=
ay: Doing it during market hours is too chaotic, and doing it overnight on =
a weekday doesn=E2=80=99t give you enough time.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-=
bottom: 5px;">Between the time that you start getting nervous and the time =
that you actually do the rescue, you have to put a brave face on things. =
=E2=80=9CStruggling Bank is doing just great, its capital and liquidity are=
 strong, it has access to very large but not at all panicky central bank li=
quidity facilities, what are you even talking about, why would anyone worry=
,=E2=80=9D you say at the press conference on Wednesday, and then you go ba=
ck to your office to continue arranging a rescue for the weekend.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is all a pretty standard playbook for, yo=
u know, once-a-decade-or-two banking crises, but it is not really=C2=A0<em>=
written down=C2=A0</em>anywhere, except eventually in the memoirs of centra=
l bankers and regulators.=C2=A0Mostly for good reasons, there will not be a=
 law saying, like, =E2=80=9Cif the national bank regulator is worried about=
 a 20% probability of an uncontrolled bank failure, she can pick a differen=
t bank and force it to buy the struggling bank over a weekend, and name her=
 own price.=E2=80=9D It=E2=80=99s just, if you are the regulator, you kind =
of know you can do that, and you know that you should, and you know that th=
e relevant bankers also know it.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so if you meet with the chief executive of=
ficer of the struggling bank on Thursday and say =E2=80=9Chey your biggest =
rival is gonna buy you this weekend at a 90% discount to your closing stock=
 price tomorrow,=E2=80=9D and he says =E2=80=9Cwhat, no, what gives you the=
 right to do that,=E2=80=9D you can just sort of stare at him for a minute =
and he=E2=80=99ll say =E2=80=9Coh right=E2=80=9D and agree to the deal.=C2=
=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">He is a banker and his counterpart is a banker=
 and you are a bank regulator and you all know the unwritten rules, but not=
 everyone does. The struggling bank=E2=80=99s=C2=A0<em>shareholders</em>, f=
or instance, might get angry about being forced to sell their shares at a 9=
0% discount. =E2=80=9CThis is illegal, we have rights,=E2=80=9D they might =
say. And your response might reasonably be =E2=80=9Cwell, no, if we hadn=E2=
=80=99t done this deal over the weekend, the bank would have gone into unco=
ntrolled failure, which would have had many very bad consequences, the <em>=
least</em> consequential of which is that your shares would be worth zero, =
so be happy you got something.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But=C2=A0<em>their </em>response might reasona=
bly be: =E2=80=9CWhat? Prove it. I don=E2=80=99t know that the bank would h=
ave gone to zero over the weekend, and in fact on Wednesday you were saying=
 that its capital position was great and there was nothing to worry about. =
Now you are telling me it=E2=80=99s a zero, but I don=E2=80=99t believe you=
.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And for various reasons, it will be=C2=A0<em>h=
ard=C2=A0</em>for you to prove that the bank was going to zero. For one thi=
ng, you <em>did=C2=A0</em>keep saying everything was fine. And there is a g=
eneral fog of war and <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cl=
ick/30911506.258434/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGV=
zLzIwMjMtMDMtMjAvdWJzLWdvdC1jcmVkaXQtc3Vpc3NlLWZvci1hbG1vc3Qtbm90aGluZz9jbX=
BpZD1CQkQwMzIxMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c=
2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzAzMjEmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b=
8524a319a23cB93dcb428" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targe=
t=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bor=
der-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: s=
olid; background-color: #ccc;">  quantum uncertainty of bank assets</a>. An=
d it is hard to prove the counterfactual: The stuff you did to stabilize th=
e system over the weekend might have<em> made</em> the struggling bank solv=
ent. Also, though, you might be wrong? Like, if you thought there was a 30%=
 chance of an uncontrolled failure, you probably took decisive steps to end=
 it over the weekend, which means there was a 70% chance you were wrong. No=
t a risk you wanted to take, as a bank regulator, but maybe one the <em>sha=
reholders</em> would have been willing to take.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or politicians might say =E2=80=9Cwhat gave yo=
u the right to do this bank merger=C2=A0over the weekend, put thousands of =
bankers out of work,=C2=A0and promise tons of taxpayer money to backstop th=
e combined bank?=E2=80=9D And you will mutter a legal answer =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0you do=C2=A0<em>have=C2=A0</em>lawyers, and they can make creative use o=
f the written rules in an emergency =E2=80=94=C2=A0but the real deep intuit=
ive answer is that bank rescues follow an unwritten and ad hoc playbook=C2=
=A0and you did what you thought you had to. But nobody wants to hear that a=
nswer and you will save it for your memoir.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Financial Times has a particularly <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30911506.258434/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvMzA4MGQzNjgtZDVhYS00MTI1LWEyMTAtNzE0ZTM3MDg3MDE3=
/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC588f9f59" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"ite=
mscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !i=
mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> brisk and brutal account</a> o=
f how the Swiss =E2=80=9Ctrinity=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0the Swiss National=
 Bank, the Financial Markets Supervisory Authority and the minister of fina=
nce =E2=80=94=C2=A0forced UBS Group AG to buy Credit Suisse Group AG over t=
he weekend. All the elements are there. There=E2=80=99s the worry about an =
uncontrolled failure due to bank run:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">By Friday evening, when it was rev=
ealed that UBS was exploring a state-mandated takeover, Credit Suisse had l=
ost another SFr35bn in client deposits over the preceding three days, accor=
ding to a banker involved in the deal, and international banks from BNP Par=
ibas to HSBC were cutting ties. Regulators concluded that it would probably=
 not be able to open on Monday.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is the peremptory order to the strugglin=
g bank:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the same meeting where they aut=
horised the SFr50bn backstop [on Wednesday], they also delivered another me=
ssage: =E2=80=9CYou will merge with UBS and announce Sunday evening before =
Asia opens. This is not optional,=E2=80=9D a person briefed on the conversa=
tion recalls.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Note that this was the=C2=A0meeting last week=
=C2=A0at which Finma and the SNB announced a liquidity backstop for Credit =
Suisse; <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30911506.2=
58434/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZmlubWEuY2gvZW4vbmV3cy8yMDIzLzAzLzIwMjMwMzE1LW1tLXN0Y=
XRlbWVudC8/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB432c2d81" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsc=
ope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> the announcement sai=
d</a> =E2=80=9CFINMA confirms that Credit Suisse meets the higher capital a=
nd liquidity requirements applicable to systemically important banks=E2=80=
=9D and that =E2=80=9Cthere are no indications of a direct risk of contagio=
n for Swiss institutions due to the current turmoil in the US banking marke=
t.=E2=80=9D Even as the regulators were telling the=C2=A0<em>market</em> th=
at everything was fine and Credit Suisse was not in trouble, they were tell=
ing <em>Credit Suisse</em>=C2=A0that it was all over.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is the peremptory order to UBS, which un=
derstood that uncontrolled failure of Credit Suisse would be a catastrophe =
for UBS as well:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The trinity called UBS and ordered the group t=
o find a solution to save its ailing peer from bankruptcy.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CResolution [a government-controlled w=
ind-down] would have been a disaster for the financial system and introduce=
d the threat of contagion around the world,=E2=80=9D says another person in=
volved on the UBS side. =E2=80=9COur interests were also aligned because a =
failure is not good for the Swiss wealth-management brand. So we said, on t=
he right terms, we would help.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There was some pushback from Credit Suisse:</p=
>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[Credit Suisse Chairman Axel] Lehmann=E2=80=99=
s communique also carried a threat. He wrote that Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s t=
hree biggest shareholders =E2=80=94 including two from Saudi Arabia and one=
 from Qatar =E2=80=94 had expressed their =E2=80=9Cextreme discomfort=E2=80=
=9D with the opacity of the deal. They demanded to see a fair price, a vote=
 on the deal and that any get-out clauses be removed. The letter also noted=
 that the Saudis and Qataris were large clients of both banks.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In response, on Saturday evening [UBS Chairman=
 Colm] Kelleher called his counterpart at Credit Suisse from outside a rest=
aurant to tell him UBS was prepared to offer $1bn in stock for the whole gr=
oup, about SFr0.25 a share, far below the SFr1.86 closing price on Friday.<=
/p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The government then informed Credit Suisse it =
would introduce emergency legislation to strip both sets of shareholders of=
 the right to vote on the deal.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Credit Suisse was outraged and refused to sign=
.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But it had no real leverage:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Under pressure to get a deal done before the e=
nd of the day, the trinity started to ramp up pressure on both sides, threa=
tening to remove the Credit Suisse board if they did not sign off. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The final terms were still so favourable to UB=
S they were =E2=80=9Can offer we couldn=E2=80=99t refuse=E2=80=9D, a person=
 on the negotiating team told the FT. An adviser to Credit Suisse described=
 them as =E2=80=9Cunacceptable and outrageous=E2=80=9D and a =E2=80=9Ctotal=
 disregard of corporate governance and shareholder rights=E2=80=9D.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the shareholders also complained<a class=
=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !=
important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Its Middle Eastern shareholders were also ince=
nsed.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CYou make fun of dictatorships and the=
n you can change the law over the weekend. What=E2=80=99s the difference be=
tween Saudi Arabia and Switzerland now? It=E2=80=99s really bad,=E2=80=9D s=
ays one person close to one of the three major shareholders.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One difference is that the Swiss regulators di=
d not bring the chairmen of Credit Suisse and UBS to a hotel and <a href=3D=
"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30911506.258434/aHR0cHM6Ly93=
d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTgtMDYtMTUvcml0ei1jYXJsdG9uLWN=
yYWNrZG93bi1zdGlsbC1oYXVudHMtdGhlLW5ldy1zYXVkaS1hcmFiaWE_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDMyMT=
IzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX=
3Rlcm09MjMwMzIxJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8a=
d933fe" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" st=
yle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-widt=
h: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgroun=
d-color: #ccc;">  torture them until they agreed</a> to the deal. (This is =
in part because the chairmen of Credit Suisse and UBS are experienced banke=
rs who know how this is supposed to go, though also for other reasons.) Sti=
ll I=C2=A0mean you can see their point. Bloomberg=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"http=
s://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30911506.258434/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY=
mxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMjAvY3JlZGl0LXN1aXNzZS1jb2xs=
YXBzZS1yZXZlYWxzLXNvbWUtdWdseS10cnV0aHMtYWJvdXQtc3dpdHplcmxhbmQtZm9yLWludmV=
zdG9ycz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMzIxMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3=
VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzAzMjEmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/6=
07f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB5b94ebfe" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"items=
cope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  Hugo Miller and Dylan Griffiths=
 write</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For decades, Switzerland has sold itself as a =
haven of legal certainty for bond and equity investors. The collapse of Cre=
dit Suisse Group AG revealed some unpleasant home truths.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the race to secure UBS Group AG=E2=80=99s p=
urchase of its smaller rival over the weekend, the government invoked the n=
eed for stability and emergency legislation to override two key aspects of =
open markets: competition law and shareholder rights. Then bondholders disc=
overed that $17 billion worth of so-called Additional Tier 1 debt was worth=
less.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Aside from the sense of shame brought on by th=
e bank=E2=80=99s collapse, legal observers say these three surprises raise =
some fundamental questions about the primacy of Swiss banking law and also =
sows doubt with foreign investors about putting money in the country.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CForeign investors may wonder if Switz=
erland is a banana republic where the rule of law doesn=E2=80=99t apply,=E2=
=80=9D said Peter V. Kunz, a professor specialized in economic law at the U=
niversity of Bern. The country =E2=80=9Cis not endangered, but there might =
be the risk of lawsuits=E2=80=9D because authorities =E2=80=9Cintervened he=
re on very thin ice.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Kern Alexander, a professor of law and finance=
 at the University of Zurich, agreed, saying crisis management was carried =
out in a =E2=80=9Cpanicked=E2=80=9D way that =E2=80=9Cundermined the rule o=
f law and undermined Switzerland.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I guess. One can always find fault with these =
rescues, in part due to fog-of-war and hard-to-prove-the-counterfactual rea=
sons and in part because, you know, why=C2=A0<em>wouldn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em=
>people panic in a crisis. But to me, the Credit Suisse rescue looks more o=
r less like the standard playbook. Which doesn=E2=80=99t mean that it follo=
wed the rules and upheld the rule of law.=C2=A0That=E2=80=99s not how these=
 things generally go.</p>
