<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For example, I <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bl=
oombergbusiness.com/click/30911506.258434/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvb=
S9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMjAvdWJzLWdvdC1jcmVkaXQtc3Vpc3NlLWZvci1h=
bG1vc3Qtbm90aGluZz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMzIxMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWl=
sJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzAzMjEmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbm=
V5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC93dcb428" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsco=
pe=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration=
: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; =
border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  wrote yesterday</a> =
about how Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s additional tier 1 capital securities were=
 zeroed by this deal, even as Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s shareholders got some=
thing (though not much). There are about 16 billion Swiss francs of AT1s ou=
tstanding, and their holders are very upset about this treatment and contem=
plating suing. The AT1s are, nominally, senior in the capital structure to =
the common stock, so it is weird for them to get nothing when the common ge=
ts something.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The AT1s are basically bonds that pay interest=
, but there is a provision in the bonds saying that they get written down t=
o zero if (1) Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s common equity tier 1 capital falls be=
low 7% or (2) the Swiss regulators decide that zeroing them is necessary to=
 keep Credit Suisse solvent.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">My point yesterday was that the first trigger =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0the 7% capital ratio trigger =E2=80=94=C2=A0<em>necessarily=
=C2=A0</em>means that the AT1s are sometimes junior to the common stock: If=
 the common equity capital ratio falls to 5%, then (1) there is value remai=
ning for the equity (5% of risk-weighted assets!) but (2) the AT1s get trig=
gered and written down to zero.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But I conceded that that is not exactly what h=
appened to Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s AT1s: Credit Suisse did not make a deter=
mination that its capital ratio=C2=A0fell below 7% and then deliver that no=
tice to the holders in accordance with the terms to force a writedown. Part=
 of the reason it did not do this was urgency, fog of war, etc.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But part of the reason is that Credit Suisse=
=E2=80=99s capital ratio never fell below 7%. A week ago, <a href=3D"https:=
//link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30911506.258434/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2V=
jLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzEwNTMwOTIvMDAwMTM3MDM2ODIzMDAwMDI2L2NzLT=
IwMjIxMjMxLmh0bSNJZDAwMTMxMDc0Mg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2afcfc51" itempro=
p=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #=
000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-=
bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"=
> Credit Suisse reported</a> that its common equity tier 1 capital ratio, a=
s of the end of 2022, was 14.1%. Last Wednesday, as I mentioned above, the =
Swiss regulators affirmed =E2=80=9Cthat Credit Suisse meets the higher capi=
tal and liquidity requirements applicable to systemically important banks,=
=E2=80=9D=C2=A0<em>as of Wednesday</em>; those requirements included a 10% =
common equity tier 1 capital ratio.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#foo=
tnote-5" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none =
!important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block=
;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then Credit Suisse sold for about CHF 3 bi=
llion to UBS over the weekend. On the one hand, an equity value of CHF 3 bi=
llion is quite small,=C2=A0roughly 0.6% of its total book assets as of the =
end of 2022, and about 1.2% of risk-weighted assets, suggesting that the=C2=
=A0<em>actual=C2=A0</em>value of Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s equity was well be=
low 7%. On the other hand, that=E2=80=99s not how capital accounting works,=
 and it seems like for accounting purposes UBS is allowed to treat Credit S=
uisse as though it=C2=A0was solvent and well capitalized and its assets wer=
e worth far more than its liabilities. UBS=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://lin=
k.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30911506.258434/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cudWJzLmNv=
bS9nbG9iYWwvZW4vaW52ZXN0b3ItcmVsYXRpb25zL19qY3JfY29udGVudC9tYWlucGFyL3RvcGx=
ldmVsZ3JpZF85NzAwNjc4XzE3NjI4NjA4MDYvY29sMS90ZWFzZXIvbGlua2xpc3QvbGlua18xMD=
UyODM5MTY0LjE5OTc5NTg1MjkuZmlsZS9QUzlqYjI1MFpXNTBMMlJoYlM5aGMzTmxkSE12WTJNd=
mFXNTJaWE4wYjNJdGNtVnNZWFJwYjI1ekwzVmljeTFoYm1RdFkzTXZkV0p6TFdOekxYQnlaWE5s=
Ym5SaGRHbHZiaTV3WkdZPS91YnMtY3MtcHJlc2VudGF0aW9uLnBkZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319=
a23cB6b81c460" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bl=
ank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; ba=
ckground-color: #ccc;"> investor presentation</a> notes that it got CHF 56 =
billion of badwill from the deal, meaning that for accounting purposes it b=
ought CHF 59 billion worth of equity for CHF 3 billion, and CHF 59 billion =
of equity would leave Credit Suisse quite well capitalized.<a class=3D"foot=
note-index" href=3D"#footnote-6" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !importan=
t; display: inline-block;">
<span>[6]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So as a matter of <em>rough justice</em>, the =
AT1s going to zero while the common stock went almost-but-not-quite to zero=
 seems very fair and expected to me. On the other hand, as a <em>legal read=
ing of the documents</em>, this argument doesn=E2=80=99t really work.=C2=A0=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Instead, the AT1s got zeroed through a more ad=
 hoc regulatory determination that it was necessary to zero them to save th=
e bank. And the problem there is (1) you can second-guess that determinatio=
n and (2) you can argue that, if it was necessary to zero the AT1s, then it=
 was=C2=A0<em>also=C2=A0</em>necessary to zero the common stock, so preserv=
ing value for the common undermines the case for zeroing the AT1s.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I am not super-sympathetic to those arguments,=
 but they are not trivial, and they are the sort of arguments that come out=
 of an ad hoc desperate weekend rescue of a big bank.=C2=A0And in particula=
r, the Swiss regulators=E2=80=99 insistence that Credit Suisse was well cap=
italized both last week (when they were trying to calm markets) and this we=
ek (when they don=E2=80=99t want to leave UBS with a giant capital hole) ma=
kes it harder for them to argue that the AT1s needed to be triggered. There=
 is a real tension between the standard regulatory responses of (1) insisti=
ng that everything is fine and also (2) taking drastic emergency actions.</=
p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway, this isn=E2=80=99t over.=C2=A0<a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30911506.258434/aHR0cHM6L=
