ext-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-co=
lor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  picked=
 the good bits</a>).</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But eventually this got a bit more standardize=
d, so that instead of paying employees in whatever weird exposures it had l=
ying around, Credit Suisse started paying part of their bonuses in one part=
icular weird exposure. It was =E2=80=A6=C2=A0oh no =E2=80=A6=C2=A0it was ad=
ditional tier 1 contingent capital securities!=C2=A0The things that got zer=
oed this weekend! Bad choice.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Except that the bonuses weren=E2=80=99t exactl=
y paid in the AT1 bonds that were publicly traded and were zeroed this week=
end. Instead, they got paid =E2=80=9CContingent Capital Awards=E2=80=9D wit=
h very similar terms, including that the awards would go to zero if capital=
 fell too low or to prevent insolvency or a public rescue.<a class=3D"footn=
ote-index" href=3D"#footnote-7" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: n=
one !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bor=
der-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important=
; display: inline-block;">
<span>[7]</span>
</a>=C2=A0So did they get zeroed over the weekend along with the public AT1=
 bonds, or not? I don=E2=80=99t know! Maybe not? Bloomberg=E2=80=99s=C2=A0<=
a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30911506.258434/aHR=
0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMjEvY3JlZGl0LX=
